Was on the hunt for traditional Trinidad 🇹🇹 corn  soup. Considered to be an after-party street food in Trinidad, by which corn soup is rich, creamy, utterly satisfying,  nourishing well seasoned with pigtail and delightfully filling. Was recommended this spot by someone who apparently has no idea what Caribbean cuisine is. I requested a small portion of their corn soup. What I got wasn’t what I’m used too. I ordered a small bowl and was expecting a scoring steaming piping hot bowl that would take me back to the streets of San Fernando on Jouvert morning.  The bowl was filled with raimen broth and some strange stringy protein which looked like jelly fish, at the bottom of the bowl was corn kernels. It looked like egg drop soup with corn. I asked the cashier what was this? She said it’s corn soup with chicken. I said “hell no it ain’t”. In all, the decor was run down, the pastries weren’t appealing and the atmosphere felt like it was dying of a come back. .....  MADE ME SOME CORN SOUP SO YOU CAN SEE WHAT REAL CORN SOUP SHOULD LOOK LIKE.

Visited and dined in here for the first time yesterday (11/17/2015). The decor was super cheesy and outdated, but for someone who was looking for some authentic Guyanese-Chinese food in a restaurant that was reminiscent of my childhood, it was perfect! My friend and I ordered the house special fried rice and house special chowmein. I'm not a fan of chowmein but he said it was delish. My house special fried rice was divine, the portions were so large I only finished half of mine and my friend finished all of his. We got Mauby and Sorrel drinks too, the sorrel was good but the mauby was mostly bitter. We also got cassava pone, polourie, pine tarts and sponge cake to go. All in all, it was a great experience, our waitress was really nice and the service was superb, would definitely recommend this place if you're looking for some good old-fashioned Guyanese-Chinese food!
